{
  "text": "Both these Aplysia sensory neuron types use glutamate (L-Glu) as their primary excitatory neurotransmitter [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Applied L-Glu activated excitatory currents in PVC and BSC sensory neurons Fieber, 2011, 2012) . D-Aspartate (DAsp) is a relevant doppelganger of L-Glu (Olverman et al., 1988) whose physiological actions have recently been studied [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In Aplysia, D-Asp activated a current pharmacologically distinct from ionotropic L-Glu receptor (iGluR) currents in PVC and BSC sensory neurons . The frequency and density of D-Asp-induced currents decreased significantly in old PVC neurons [CITATION_7] , suggesting that sensory neuron excitability is affected during aging in this model organism.",
  "correct_citation": {
